	   <tr><td colspan=2>1. I haven't been there yet, but website says 20 - 30.  I'd guess you'd be ok at 20 in a good group.<br><br>2.  I may regret it later, but I've been going for str, over all others.  The way I figure it, the more damage you dish out, the faster the mob dies, the less damage the tank takes.  Monks are supposed to be damage dealers and not tanks, although I usually end up tanking because the group I'm in does not have a true tank.  But if you have a taunter, and you're dealing too much damage, just feign death to lower yourself on the hate list.<br><br>3.  No experience with either of these yet.  I'll just go by the stats when I decided to do either.<br><br>4.  When you start getting up there in level, copper will be totally meaningless.  I drop it all.  Save your pp and gold.  I give all my silver away to someone in my group, in exchange for them banking for me.  I usually group with a druid that can bind themselves, TP out and bank and then just gate back.  This helps to sell stuff too, I have my druid friend do it for me (of course wizzie can do it also)  If you want to solo, try fighting something that drops gems, which seems to be a lot of 30s mobs.  They weigh only 0.1 and sell fairly well.  I'm lvl 35 now and have bought a few items, but have accumulated about 3500 PP so far, I'm saving for a haste item, probably fbss.<br><br>Speaking of haste items, I think (and probably most of the high level monks will agree) that a haste item becomes crucial at higher levels.  I was grouped with an enchanter and when they cast alacrity (haste) on me, I was amazed at the speed at which I was hitting.  Spell caster mobs? Forget em, they'll never get a spell off when you hit that fast, you'll keep interrupting.<br><br>Good luck<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
